Introduction
nflammatory disorders of the central nervous system () such as multiple sclerosis () are often accompanied by substantial damage to axons and myelin (1). he extent of axonal damage is of particular importance for the clinical deficit that  patients accumulate over time (2, 3). owever, the clinical outcome will ultimately depend on the balance of damage inflicted on the  and the extent of endogenous repair that can counter it. lthough axonal destruction in  has been characterized extensively in recent years, very little is known about how it can be counterbalanced (4, 5). ubstantial compensation is evident in the typical clinical course of . he relapsingβ€“remitting form of the disease is defined by cycles of newly emerging clinical deficits that resolve within a few days or weeks. he regression of tissue edema and inflammation undoubtedly plays a major role early during remission, but these processes cannot mend structural damage caused by the inflammatory attack. hus, additional compensatory mechanisms must be considered for complete recovery that often occurs despite substantial structural damage that persists at the site of inflammation.
he neuropathology of  and its animal model, experimental autoimmune encephalomyelitis (), suggests that limited repair of myelin damage can be achieved (β€�remyelinationβ€�), when oligodendrocytes form new myelin (5, 6) his gives rise to so-called shadow plaques, which are areas of myelin pallor in  brain tissue. n addition, the redistribution of sodium-channels in demyelinated axons can help to compensate for myelin loss (7). owever, given the close correlation between the extent of axon damage and clinical deficit in , one would expect compensation for axon loss to be an even more powerful means of recovery. urprisingly, little is known about how lost axonal connections are repaired in . arly papers have documented changes suggestive of axonal outgrowth in lesions of , a finding subsequently confirmed for  (8β€“10). n addition, functional  studies provide evidence for cortical adaptation in  patients (11, 12). he lack of understanding of how recovery from axonal damage occurs in  is, in part, due to the disseminated nature of  and . ultiple neuroinflammatory lesions occur in unpredictable locations in these diseases and damage various axonal tracts with high interindividual variability. his makes the analysis of axonal compensation, which occurs equally in a disseminated and variable way, difficult if not impossible.
n the present paper, we have circumvented this problem by using a recently developed β€�targetedβ€�  model in which we can reproducibly induce a single inflammatory, demyelinating lesion in the dorsal column area of the midthoracic spinal cord (13). his area comprises the corticospinal tract (), a major descending motor tract that connects cortical layer  neurons with spinal targets and is often affected in  (14). argeting lesions to this tract system combined with detection of growth-associated proteins, as well as a variety of anterograde, retrograde, and trans-synaptic tracing techniques allowed us to analyze precisely how axonal compensation is achieved. e demonstrate that a single  lesion in the spinal cord induces axonal remodeling on many levels: (a) on the spinal level, in the neuronal circuitry surrounding the lesion, where numerous axons sprout; (b) in descending motor tracts, which create β€�detourβ€� circuits to circumnavigate the lesion; and (c) at the cortical level, where the map of motor neurons that project to spinal motor targets is remodeled. inally, behavioral experiments show that at least some of these remodeled connections directly contribute to functional recovery.
