Results
his work explores how axonal damage is compensated for in an animal model of . e approached this problem in a reductionist way, by studying the compensatory response of the motor system to a single, localized neuroinflammatory lesion.  targeted  lesion was induced in the dorsal column of the midthoracic spinal cord by minimal invasive injection of proinflammatory cytokines in rats immunized with subthreshold levels of (13). reviously, we had established that these targeted lesions reflect the major pathological hallmarks of , including focal inflammatory demyelination and extensive axonal damage (13). e have now characterized the evolution of inflammation, demyelination, and axonal damage in these lesions over time (ig. 1). fter the cytokine injection, a large inflammatory infiltration developed within a few days (ig. 1 a, 7). owever, both the area of inflammation (ig. 1 d) as well as the density of cell infiltration (day 7: 4229 ± 379; day 14: 5503 ± 848; and day 28: 5428 ± 406 cells/mm2) remained largely unchanged for the remaining experimental period (days 7β€“28). arameters of structural damage showed a similar time course. xtensive demyelination occurred up to day 7, but the area of demyelination did not change significantly between days 7 and 28 (ig. 1, eβ€“h). e did not detect remyelination at any time point. he axon density dropped substantially over the first days of lesion development and again remained unchanged from day 7 up to day 28 (ig. 1, iβ€“l). n accordance with this finding, acute axonal damage, as assessed by immunohistochemistry for , was prominent at an early disease stage (ig. 1 m, 7) and substantially lower at later stages (ig. 1, n and o, 14, 28). owever, despite the persistent structural damage, the animals showed a nearly complete behavioral recovery over the same time period (ig. 1 p). hese findings point to the existence of compensatory mechanisms, which promote behavioral recovery in the presence of persisting structural deficits. he targeted  model now allows us to analyze these compensatory mechanisms on multiple anatomical levels.
